# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: openmp-parallelism
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] A data parallel job on an array of *n* elements can be divided equally among all the processors.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] Let us assume we want to sum all the elements of the given array and the time for a single addition operation is Ta time units.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] In the case of sequential execution, the time taken by the process will be *n*×Ta time units as it sums up all the elements of an array.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] On the other hand, if we execute this job as a data parallel job on 4 processors the time taken would reduce to (*n*/4)×Ta + merging overhead time units.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] Parallel execution results in a speedup of 4 over sequential execution.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] The locality of data references plays an important part in evaluating the performance of a data parallel programming model.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] Locality of data depends on the memory accesses performed by the program as well as the size of the cache.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] Exploitation of the concept of data parallelism started in 1960s with the development of the Solomon machine.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] The Solomon machine, also called a vector processor, was developed to expedite the performance of mathematical operations by working on a large data array (operating on multiple data in consecutive time steps).
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] Concurrency of data operations was also exploited by operating on multiple data at the same time using a single instruction.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] These processors were called 'array processors'.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] In the 1980s, the term was introduced to describe this programming style, which was widely used to program Connection Machines in data parallel languages like C*.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] Today, data parallelism is best exemplified in graphics processing units (GPUs), which use both the techniques of operating on multiple data in space and time using a single instruction.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] Most data parallel hardware supports only a fixed number of parallel levels, often only one.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] This means that within a parallel operation it is not possible to launch more parallel operations recursively, and means that programmers cannot make use of nested hardware parallelism.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] The programming language NESL was an early effort at implementing a nested data-parallel programming model on flat parallel machines, and in particular introduced the flattening transformation that transforms nested data parallelism to flat data parallelism.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] This work was continued by other languages such as Data Parallel Haskell and Futhark, although arbitrary nested data parallelism is not widely available in current data-parallel programming languages.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] In a multiprocessor system executing a single set of instructions (SIMD), data parallelism is achieved when each processor performs the same task on different distributed data.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] In some situations, a single execution thread controls operations on all the data.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] In others, different threads control the operation, but they execute the same code.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] For instance, consider matrix multiplication and addition in a sequential manner as discussed in the example.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] Below is the sequential pseudo-code for multiplication and addition of two matrices where the result is stored in the matrix *C*.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] The pseudo-code for multiplication calculates the dot product of two matrices *A*, *B* and stores the result into the output matrix *C*.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] If the following programs were executed sequentially, the time taken to calculate the result would be of the $O(n^{3})$ (assuming row lengths and column lengths of both matrices are n) and $O(n)$ for multiplication and addition respectively.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] We can exploit data parallelism in the preceding code to execute it faster as the arithmetic is loop independent.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] Parallelization of the matrix multiplication code is achieved by using OpenMP.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] An OpenMP directive, "omp parallel for" instructs the compiler to execute the code in the for loop in parallel.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] For multiplication, we can divide matrix A and B into blocks along rows and columns respectively.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] This allows us to calculate every element in matrix C individually thereby making the task parallel.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] For example: *A[m x n] dot B [n x k]* can be finished in $O(n)$ instead of $O(m*n*k)$ when executed in parallel using *m*k* processors.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] It can be observed from the example that a lot of processors will be required as the matrix sizes keep on increasing.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] Keeping the execution time low is the priority but as the matrix size increases, we are faced with other constraints like complexity of such a system and its associated costs.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] Therefore, constraining the number of processors in the system, we can still apply the same principle and divide the data into bigger chunks to calculate the product of two matrices.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] For addition of arrays in a data parallel implementation, let's assume a more modest system with two central processing units (CPU) A and B, CPU A could add all elements from the top half of the arrays, while CPU B could add all elements from the bottom half of the arrays.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] Since the two processors work in parallel, the job of performing array addition would take one half the time of performing the same operation in serial using one CPU alone.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] In an SPMD system executed on 2 processor system, both CPUs will execute the code.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] Data parallelism emphasizes the distributed (parallel) nature of the data, as opposed to the processing (task parallelism).
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] Most real programs fall somewhere on a continuum between task parallelism and data parallelism.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] The process of parallelizing a sequential program can be broken down into four discrete steps.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] Data and task parallelism, can be simultaneously implemented by combining them together for the same application.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] This is called Mixed data and task parallelism.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] Mixed parallelism requires sophisticated scheduling algorithms and software support.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] It is the best kind of parallelism when communication is slow and number of processors is large.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] Mixed data and task parallelism has many applications.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] The data is divided among different sub-circuits and parallelism is achieved with orchestration from the tasks.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] OpenMP: It's an Application Programming Interface (API) which supports shared memory programming models on multiple platforms of multiprocessor systems.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] Since version 4.5, OpenMP is also able to target devices other than typical CPUs.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] It can program FPGAs, DSPs, GPUs and more.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] It is not confined to GPUs like OpenACC.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] CUDA and OpenACC: CUDA and OpenACC (respectively) are parallel computing API platforms designed to allow a software engineer to utilize GPUs' computational units for general purpose processing.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] Threading Building Blocks and RaftLib: Both open source programming environments that enable mixed data/task parallelism in C/C++ environments across heterogeneous resources.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] Data parallelism finds its applications in a variety of fields ranging from physics, chemistry, biology, material sciences to signal processing.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] Sciences imply data parallelism for simulating models like molecular dynamics, sequence analysis of genome data and other physical phenomenon.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] Driving forces in signal processing for data parallelism are video encoding, image and graphics processing, wireless communications to name a few.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] Data-intensive computing is a class of parallel computing applications which use a data parallel approach to process large volumes of data typically terabytes or petabytes in size and typically referred to as big data.
[src:openmp-parallelism/data-parallelism] Computing applications that devote most of their execution time to computational requirements are deemed compute-intensive, whereas applications are deemed data-intensive if they require large volumes of data and devote most of their processing time to input/output and manipulation of data.
[src:openmp-parallelism/fork-join-model] In parallel computing, the **fork–join model** is a way of setting up and executing parallel programs, such that execution branches off in parallel at designated points in the program, to "join" (merge) at a subsequent point and resume sequential execution.
[src:openmp-parallelism/fork-join-model] Parallel sections may fork recursively until a certain task granularity is reached.
[src:openmp-parallelism/fork-join-model] Fork–join can be considered a parallel design pattern.
[src:openmp-parallelism/fork-join-model] The simple parallel merge sort of CLRS is a fork–join algorithm.
[src:openmp-parallelism/fork-join-model] The first recursive call is "forked off", meaning that its execution may run in parallel (in a separate thread) with the following part of the function, up to the join that causes all threads to synchronize.
[src:openmp-parallelism/fork-join-model] While the join may look like a barrier, it is different because the threads will continue to work after a barrier, while after a join only one thread continues.
[src:openmp-parallelism/fork-join-model] The second recursive call is not a fork in the pseudocode above; this is intentional, as forking tasks may come at an expense.
[src:openmp-parallelism/fork-join-model] If both recursive calls were set up as subtasks, the main task would not have any additional work to perform before being blocked at the join.
[src:openmp-parallelism/fork-join-model] The reason for this design is that creating new threads tends to result in too much overhead.
[src:openmp-parallelism/fork-join-model] The lightweight threads used in fork–join programming will typically have their own scheduler (typically a work stealing one) that maps them onto the underlying thread pool.
[src:openmp-parallelism/fork-join-model] This scheduler can be much simpler than a fully featured, preemptive operating system scheduler: general-purpose thread schedulers must deal with blocking for locks, but in the fork–join paradigm, threads only block at the join point.
[src:openmp-parallelism/fork-join-model] Fork–join is the main model of parallel execution in the OpenMP framework, although OpenMP implementations may or may not support nesting of parallel sections.
[src:openmp-parallelism/fork-join-model] It is also supported by the Java concurrency framework, the Task Parallel Library for .NET, and Intel's Threading Building Blocks (TBB).
[src:openmp-parallelism/fork-join-model] The Cilk programming language has language-level support for fork and join, in the form of the `spawn` and `sync` keywords, or `cilk_spawn` and `cilk_sync` in Cilk Plus.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] For simple loops, where each iteration is independent of the others, loop-level parallelism can be embarrassingly parallel, as parallelizing only requires assigning a process to handle each iteration.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] However, many algorithms are designed to run sequentially, and fail when parallel processes race due to dependence within the code.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] Sequential algorithms are sometimes applicable to parallel contexts with slight modification.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] Usually, though, they require process synchronization.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] Synchronization can be either implicit, via message passing, or explicit, via synchronization primitives like semaphores.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] Consider the following code operating on a list `l`, where `l.size() == n`.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] Each iteration of the loop takes the value from the current index of `l`, and increments it by 10.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] If statement `s1` takes `T` time to execute, then the loop takes time `n * T` to execute sequentially, ignoring time taken by loop constructs.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] Now, consider a system with `p` processors where `p > n`.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] If `n` threads run in parallel, the time to execute all `n` steps is reduced to `T`.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] Less simple cases produce inconsistent, i.e. non-serializable outcomes.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] Consider the following loop operating on the same list `l`.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] Each iteration sets the current index to be the value of the previous plus ten.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] When run sequentially, each iteration is guaranteed that the previous iteration will already have the correct value.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] With multiple threads, process scheduling and other considerations prevent the execution order from guaranteeing an iteration will execute only after its dependence is met.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] It very well may happen before, leading to unexpected results.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] Serializability can be restored by adding synchronization to preserve the dependence on previous iterations.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] There are several types of dependences that can be found within code.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] In order to preserve the sequential behaviour of a loop when run in parallel, True Dependence must be preserved.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] Anti-Dependence and Output Dependence can be dealt with by giving each process its own copy of variables (known as privatization).
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] `s2 ->T s3`, meaning that s2 has a true dependence on s3 because s2 writes to the variable `a`, which s3 reads from.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] `s2 ->A s3`, meaning that s2 has an anti-dependence on s3 because s2 reads from the variable `b` before s3 writes to it.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] `s2 ->O s3`, meaning that s2 has an output dependence on s3 because both write to the variable `a`.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] `s2 ->I s3`, meaning that s2 has an input dependence on s3 because s2 and s3 both read from variable `c`.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] In loop-independent dependence, loops have inter-iteration dependence, but do not have dependence between iterations.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] Each iteration may be treated as a block and performed in parallel without other synchronization efforts.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] In the following example code used for swapping the values of two array of length n, there is a loop-independent dependence of `s1 ->T s3`.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] In loop-carried dependence, statements in an iteration of a loop depend on statements in another iteration of the loop.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] Loop-Carried Dependence uses a modified version of the dependence notation seen earlier.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] Example of loop-carried dependence where `s1[i] ->T s1[i + 1]`, where `i` indicates the current iteration, and `i + 1` indicates the next iteration.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] A Loop-carried dependence graph graphically shows the loop-carried dependencies between iterations.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] Each iteration is listed as a node on the graph, and directed edges show the true, anti, and output dependencies between each iteration.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] There are a variety of methodologies for parallelizing loops.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] Each implementation varies slightly in how threads synchronize, if at all.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] In addition, parallel tasks must somehow be mapped to a process.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] These tasks can either be allocated statically or dynamically.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] Research has shown that load-balancing can be better achieved through some dynamic allocation algorithms than when done statically.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] The process of parallelizing a sequential program can be broken down into the following discrete steps.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] Each concrete loop-parallelization below implicitly performs them.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] When a loop has a loop-carried dependence, one way to parallelize it is to distribute the loop into several different loops.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] Statements that are not dependent on each other are separated so that these distributed loops can be executed in parallel.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] For example, consider the following code.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] The loop has a loop carried dependence `s1[i] ->T s1[i + 1]` but s2 and s1 do not have a loop-independent dependence so we can rewrite the code as follows.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] Note that now loop1 and loop2 can be executed in parallel.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] Instead of single instruction being performed in parallel on different data as in data level parallelism, here different loops perform different tasks on different data.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] We call this type of parallelism either function or task parallelism.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] DOALL parallelism exists when statements within a loop can be executed independently (situations where there is no loop-carried dependence).
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] For example, the following code does not read from the array `a`, and does not update the arrays `b, c`.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] No iterations have a dependence on any other iteration.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] The following example, using a simplified pseudo code, shows how a loop might be parallelized to execute each iteration independently.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] DOACROSS Parallelism exists where iterations of a loop are parallelized by extracting calculations that can be performed independently and running them simultaneously.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] Synchronization exists to enforce loop-carried dependence.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] Consider the following, synchronous loop with dependence `s1[i] ->T s1[i + 1]`.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] The first line, `int tmp = b[i] + 1;`, has no loop-carried dependence.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] The loop can then be parallelized by computing the temp value in parallel, and then synchronizing the assignment to `a[i]`.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] DOPIPE Parallelism implements pipelined parallelism for loop-carried dependence where a loop iteration is distributed over multiple, synchronized loops.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] The goal of DOPIPE is to act like an assembly line, where one stage is started as soon as there is sufficient data available for it from the previous stage.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] Consider the following, synchronous code with dependence `s1[i] ->T s1[i + 1]`.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] s1 must be executed sequentially, but s2 has no loop-carried dependence. s2 could be executed in parallel using DOALL Parallelism after performing all calculations needed by s1 in series.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] However, the speedup is limited if this is done.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] A better approach is to parallelize such that the s2 corresponding to each s1 executes when said s1 is finished.
[src:openmp-parallelism/loop-level-parallelism] Implementing pipelined parallelism results in the following set of loops, where the second loop may execute for an index as soon as the first loop has finished its corresponding index.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] OpenMP uses a portable, scalable model that gives programmers a simple and flexible interface for developing parallel applications for platforms ranging from the standard desktop computer to the supercomputer.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] An application built with the hybrid model of parallel programming can run on a computer cluster using both OpenMP and Message Passing Interface (MPI), such that OpenMP is used for parallelism *within* a (multi-core) node while MPI is used for parallelism *between* nodes.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] There have also been efforts to run OpenMP on software distributed shared memory systems, to translate OpenMP into MPI and to extend OpenMP for non-shared memory systems.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] OpenMP is an implementation of multithreading, a method of parallelizing whereby a *primary* thread (a series of instructions executed consecutively) *forks* a specified number of *sub*-threads and the system divides a task among them.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] The threads then run concurrently, with the runtime environment allocating threads to different processors.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] The section of code that is meant to run in parallel is marked accordingly, with a compiler directive that will cause the threads to form before the section is executed.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] Each thread has an *ID* attached to it which can be obtained using a function (called `omp_get_thread_num()`).
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] The thread ID is an integer, and the primary thread has an ID of *0*.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] After the execution of the parallelized code, the threads *join* back into the primary thread, which continues onward to the end of the program.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] By default, each thread executes the parallelized section of code independently.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] *Work-sharing constructs* can be used to divide a task among the threads so that each thread executes its allocated part of the code.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] Both task parallelism and data parallelism can be achieved using OpenMP in this way.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] The runtime environment allocates threads to processors depending on usage, machine load and other factors.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] The runtime environment can assign the number of threads based on environment variables, or the code can do so using functions.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] The OpenMP functions are included in a header file labelled omp.h in C/C++.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] The OpenMP Architecture Review Board (ARB) published its first API specifications, OpenMP for Fortran 1.0, in October 1997.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] In October the following year they released the C/C++ standard.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] 2000 saw version 2.0 of the Fortran specifications with version 2.0 of the C/C++ specifications being released in 2002.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] Version 2.5 is a combined C/C++/Fortran specification that was released in 2005.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] Up to version 2.0, OpenMP primarily specified ways to parallelize highly regular loops, as they occur in matrix-oriented numerical programming, where the number of iterations of the loop is known at entry time.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] This was recognized as a limitation, and various task parallel extensions were added to implementations.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] In 2005, an effort to standardize task parallelism was formed, which published a proposal in 2007, taking inspiration from task parallelism features in Cilk, X10 and Chapel.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] Included in the new features in 3.0 is the concept of *tasks* and the *task* construct, significantly broadening the scope of OpenMP beyond the parallel loop constructs that made up most of OpenMP 2.0.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] OpenMP 3.1 was released in September 2011, enhancing tasking with features like task finalization (final clause) and task dependencies (depend clause).
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] It also improved support for Fortran 2003 and added atomic construct enhancements.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] Version 4.0 of the specification was released in July 2013.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] It adds or improves the following features: support for accelerators; atomics; error handling; thread affinity; tasking extensions; user defined reduction; SIMD support; Fortran 2003 support.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] OpenMP 4.0 (2013) also introduced support for accelerators (e.g., GPUs) via the target directive, enabling offloading computations to devices like GPUs or FPGAs.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] It also added SIMD (Single Instruction, Multiple Data) directives for vectorization and user-defined reductions.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] Version 4.5 (2015) enhanced device support, improved tasking with dependencies, and introduced loop transformations for better optimization.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] Version 5.0 (2018) added significant features like memory management for accelerators, support for deep copy in target directives, and loop transformation constructs.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] It also improved interoperability with other programming models like MPI.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] OpenMP 5.1 (2020) focused on usability, adding features like loop fusion, improved task reduction, and better support for C++11/14/17 constructs.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] Version 5.2 (2021) refined existing features, improved compatibility with modern hardware, and added support for descriptive loop directives..
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] Version 6.0 was released in November 2024.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] This version focuses on enhancing OpenMP for heterogeneous computing, integrating with AI/ML workloads, and improving performance portability across diverse architectures.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] Note that not all compilers (and OSes) support the full set of features for the latest version/s.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] The core elements of OpenMP are the constructs for thread creation, workload distribution (work sharing), data-environment management, thread synchronization, user-level runtime routines and environment variables.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] The OpenMP specific pragmas are listed below.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] The pragma `omp parallel` is used to fork additional threads to carry out the work enclosed in the construct in parallel.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] The original thread will be denoted as `master thread` with thread ID 0.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] Example (C program): Display "Hello, world." using multiple threads.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] However, the output may also be garbled because of the race condition caused from the two threads sharing the standard output.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] Whether `printf` is atomic depends on the underlying implementation unlike C++11's `std::cout`, which is thread-safe by default.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] Used to specify how to assign independent work to one or all of the threads.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] This example is embarrassingly parallel, and depends only on the value of `i`.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] The OpenMP `parallel for` flag tells the OpenMP system to split this task among its working threads.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] The threads will each receive a unique and private version of the variable.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] For instance, with two worker threads, one thread might be handed a version of `i` that runs from 0 to 49999 while the second gets a version running from 50000 to 99999.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] Variant directives are one of the major features introduced in OpenMP 5.0 specification to facilitate programmers to improve performance portability.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] They enable adaptation of OpenMP pragmas and user code at compile time.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] The mechanism provided by the two variant directives for selecting variants is more convenient to use than the C/C++ preprocessing since it directly supports variant selection in OpenMP and allows an OpenMP compiler to analyze and determine the final directive from variants and context.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] Since OpenMP is a shared memory programming model, most variables in OpenMP code are visible to all threads by default.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] `dynamic`: Here, some of the iterations are allocated to a smaller number of threads.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] Once a particular thread finishes its allocated iteration, it returns to get another one from the iterations that are left.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] The parameter `chunk` defines the number of contiguous iterations that are allocated to a thread at a time.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] `guided`: A large chunk of contiguous iterations are allocated to each thread dynamically (as above).
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] A method to alter the execution features of OpenMP applications.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] Used to control loop iterations scheduling, default number of threads, etc.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] For example, `OMP_NUM_THREADS` is used to specify number of threads for an application.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] OpenMP has been implemented in many commercial compilers.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] For instance, Visual C++ 2005, 2008, 2010, 2012 and 2013 support it (OpenMP 2.0, in Professional, Team System, Premium and Ultimate editions), as well as Intel Parallel Studio for various processors.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] Oracle Solaris Studio compilers and tools support the latest OpenMP specifications with productivity enhancements for Solaris OS (UltraSPARC and x86/x64) and Linux platforms.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] The Fortran, C and C++ compilers from The Portland Group also support OpenMP 2.5.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] GCC has also supported OpenMP since version 4.2.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] One might expect to get an *N* times speedup when running a program parallelized using OpenMP on a *N* processor platform.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] Some vendors recommend setting the processor affinity on OpenMP threads to associate them with particular processor cores.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] This minimizes thread migration and context-switching cost among cores.
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] It also improves the data locality and reduces the cache-coherency traffic among the cores (or processors).
[src:openmp-parallelism/openmp] A variety of benchmarks has been developed to demonstrate the use of OpenMP, test its performance and evaluate correctness.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] In computer science, **shared memory** is memory that may be simultaneously accessed by multiple programs with an intent to provide communication among them or avoid redundant copies.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] Shared memory is an efficient means of passing data between programs.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] Depending on context, programs may run on a single processor or on multiple separate processors.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] Using memory for communication inside a single program, e.g. among its multiple threads, is also referred to as shared memory.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] In computer hardware, *shared memory* refers to a (typically large) block of random access memory (RAM) that can be accessed by several different central processing units (CPUs) in a multiprocessor computer system.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] A shared memory system is relatively easy to program since all processors share a single view of data and the communication between processors can be as fast as memory accesses to the same location.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] Technologies like crossbar switches, Omega networks, HyperTransport or front-side bus can be used to dampen the bottleneck-effects.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] The alternatives to shared memory are distributed memory and distributed shared memory, each having a similar set of issues.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] Since both processes can access the shared memory area like regular working memory, this is a very fast way of communication (as opposed to other mechanisms of IPC such as named pipes, Unix domain sockets or CORBA).
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] IPC by shared memory is used for example to transfer images between the application and the X server on Unix systems, or inside the IStream object returned by CoMarshalInterThreadInterfaceInStream in the COM libraries under Windows.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] Compared to multiple address space operating systems, memory sharing -- especially of sharing procedures or pointer-based structures -- is simpler in single address space operating systems.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] POSIX provides a standardized API for using shared memory, *POSIX Shared Memory*.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] This uses the function `shm_open` from sys/mman.h.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] POSIX interprocess communication (part of the POSIX:XSI Extension) includes the shared-memory functions `shmat`, `shmctl`, `shmdt` and `shmget`.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] Unix System V provides an API for shared memory as well.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] BSD systems provide "anonymous mapped memory" which can be used by several processes.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] The shared memory created by `shm_open` is persistent.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] It stays in the system until explicitly removed by a process.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] This has a drawback in that if the process crashes and fails to clean up shared memory it will stay until system shutdown; that limitation is not present in an Android-specific implementation dubbed `ashmem`.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] POSIX also provides the `mmap` API for mapping files into memory; a mapping can be shared, allowing the file's contents to be used as shared memory.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] Linux distributions based on the 2.6 kernel and later offer /dev/shm as shared memory in the form of a RAM disk, more specifically as a world-writable directory (a directory in which every user of the system can create files) that is stored in memory.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] Both the RedHat and Debian based distributions include it by default.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] Support for this type of RAM disk is completely optional within the kernel configuration file.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] On Windows, one can use `CreateFileMapping` and `MapViewOfFile` functions to map a region of a file into memory in multiple processes.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] Some C++ libraries provide a portable and object-oriented access to shared memory functionality.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] For example, Boost contains the Boost.Interprocess C++ Library and Qt provides the QSharedMemory class.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] For programming languages with POSIX bindings (say, C/C++), shared memory regions can be created and accessed by calling the functions provided by the operating system.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] Other programming languages may have their own ways of using these operating facilities for similar effect.
[src:openmp-parallelism/shared-memory-interprocess-communication] For example, PHP provides an API to create shared memory, similar to POSIX functions.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] In computer science, a **thread** of execution is the smallest sequence of programmed instructions that can be managed independently by a scheduler, which is typically a part of the operating system.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] In many cases, a thread is a component of a process.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] The multiple threads of a given process may be executed concurrently (via multithreading capabilities), sharing resources such as memory, while different processes do not share these resources.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] In particular, the threads of a process share its executable code and the values of its dynamically allocated variables and non-thread-local global variables at any given time.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] The implementation of threads and processes differs between operating systems.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Threads made an early appearance under the name of "tasks" in IBM's batch processing operating system, OS/360, in 1967.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] It provided users with three available configurations of the OS/360 control system, of which multiprogramming with a variable number of tasks (MVT) was one.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] The Mach implementation of threads was described in the summer of 1986.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] OS/2 1.0, released in 1987, supported threads.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Digital Research's MP/M operating system provided multiprogramming, multi-tasking, and preemptive multi-tasking for the Intel 8080 processor in 1979, and on the 8086 processor in 1981.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] The first version of Windows to have threads was Windows NT, which was released in 1993.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] In 1995, the IEEE defined the pthreads API, which standardized an interface for portable multithreaded programming across a variety of Unix-like operating systems.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Since then, pthreads has also been implemented on Windows with third-party packages such as *pthreads-w32*, which implements the standard on top of the existing Windows API.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] The use of threads in software applications became more common in the early 2000s as CPUs began to utilize multiple cores.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Applications wishing to take advantage of multiple cores for performance advantages were required to employ concurrency to utilize the multiple cores.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Scheduling can be done at the kernel level or user level, and multitasking can be done preemptively or cooperatively.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] This yields a variety of related concepts.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] At the kernel level, a *process* contains one or more *kernel threads*, which share the process's resources, such as memory and file handles – a process is a unit of resources, while a thread is a unit of scheduling and execution.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Kernel scheduling is typically uniformly done preemptively or, less commonly, cooperatively.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] At the user level a process such as a runtime system can itself schedule multiple threads of execution.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] If these do not share data, as in Erlang, they are usually analogously called processes, while if they share data they are usually called *(user) threads*, particularly if preemptively scheduled.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Cooperatively scheduled user threads are known as *fibers*; different processes may schedule user threads differently.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] User threads may be executed by kernel threads in various ways (one-to-one, many-to-one, many-to-many).
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] The term *light-weight process* variously refers to user threads or to kernel mechanisms for scheduling user threads onto kernel threads.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] A process is a heavyweight unit of kernel scheduling, as creating, destroying, and switching processes is relatively expensive.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Processes own resources allocated by the operating system.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Resources include memory (for both code and data), file handles, sockets, device handles, windows, and a process control block.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Processes are *isolated* by process isolation, and do not share address spaces or file resources except through explicit methods such as inheriting file handles or shared memory segments, or mapping the same file in a shared way – see Interprocess communication.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Creating or destroying a process is relatively expensive, as resources must be acquired or released.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] A *kernel thread* is a lightweight unit of kernel scheduling.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] At least one kernel thread exists within each process.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] If multiple kernel threads exist within a process, then they share the same memory and file resources.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Kernel threads are preemptively multitasked if the operating system's process scheduler is preemptive.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Kernel threads do not own resources except for a stack, a copy of the registers including the program counter, and thread-local storage (if any), and are thus relatively cheap to create and destroy.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Thread switching is also relatively cheap: it requires a context switch (saving and restoring registers and stack pointer), but does not change virtual memory and is thus cache-friendly (leaving TLB valid).
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] The kernel can assign one or more software threads to each core in a CPU (it being able to assign itself multiple software threads depending on its support for multithreading), and can swap out threads that get blocked.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] However, kernel threads take much longer than user threads to be swapped.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Threads are sometimes implemented in userspace libraries, thus called *user threads*.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] The kernel is unaware of them, so they are managed and scheduled in userspace.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Some implementations base their user threads on top of several kernel threads, to benefit from multi-processor machines (M:N model).
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] User threads as implemented by virtual machines are also called green threads.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Since scheduling occurs in userspace, the scheduling policy can be more easily tailored to the requirements of the program's workload.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] However, the use of blocking system calls in user threads (as opposed to kernel threads) can be problematic.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] If a user thread or a fiber performs a system call that blocks, the other user threads and fibers in the process are unable to run until the system call returns.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] A typical example of this problem is when performing I/O: most programs are written to perform I/O synchronously.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] When an I/O operation is initiated, a system call is made, and does not return until the I/O operation has been completed.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] In the intervening period, the entire process is "blocked" by the kernel and cannot run, which starves other user threads and fibers in the same process from executing.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Similar solutions can be provided for other blocking system calls.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Alternatively, the program can be written to avoid the use of synchronous I/O or other blocking system calls (in particular, using non-blocking I/O, including lambda continuations and/or async/await primitives).
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Fibers are an even lighter unit of scheduling which are cooperatively scheduled: a running fiber must explicitly *yield* to allow another fiber to run, which makes their implementation much easier than kernel or user threads.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] A fiber can be scheduled to run in any thread in the same process.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] This permits applications to gain performance improvements by managing scheduling themselves, instead of relying on the kernel scheduler (which may not be tuned for the application).
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Some research implementations of the OpenMP parallel programming model implement their tasks through fibers.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Closely related to fibers are coroutines, with the distinction being that coroutines are a language-level construct, while fibers are a system-level construct.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Operating systems schedule threads either preemptively or cooperatively.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Multi-user operating systems generally favor preemptive multithreading for its finer-grained control over execution time via context switching.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] However, preemptive scheduling may context-switch threads at moments unanticipated by programmers, thus causing lock convoy, priority inversion, or other side-effects.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] In contrast, cooperative multithreading relies on threads to relinquish control of execution, thus ensuring that threads run to completion.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] This can cause problems if a cooperatively-multitasked thread blocks by waiting on a resource or if it starves other threads by not yielding control of execution during intensive computation.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Until the early 2000s, most desktop computers had only one single-core CPU, with no support for hardware threads, although threads were still used on such computers because switching between threads was generally still quicker than full-process context switches.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] In 2002, Intel added support for simultaneous multithreading to the Pentium 4 processor, under the name *hyper-threading*; in 2005, they introduced the dual-core Pentium D processor and AMD introduced the dual-core Athlon 64 X2 processor.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Systems with a single processor generally implement multithreading by time slicing: the central processing unit (CPU) switches between different *software threads*.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] This context switching usually occurs frequently enough that users perceive the threads or tasks as running in parallel (for popular server/desktop operating systems, maximum time slice of a thread, when other threads are waiting, is often limited to 100–200ms).
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] On a multiprocessor or multi-core system, multiple threads can execute in parallel, with every processor or core executing a separate thread simultaneously; on a processor or core with *hardware threads*, separate software threads can also be executed concurrently by separate hardware threads.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Threads created by the user in a 1:1 correspondence with schedulable entities in the kernel are the simplest possible threading implementation.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] OS/2 and Win32 used this approach from the start, while on Linux the GNU C Library implements this approach (via the NPTL or older LinuxThreads).
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] This approach is also used by Solaris, NetBSD, FreeBSD, macOS, and iOS.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] An *M*:1 model implies that all application-level threads map to one kernel-level scheduled entity; the kernel has no knowledge of the application threads.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] With this approach, context switching can be done very quickly and, in addition, it can be implemented even on simple kernels which do not support threading.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] One of the major drawbacks, however, is that it cannot benefit from the hardware acceleration on multithreaded processors or multi-processor computers: there is never more than one thread being scheduled at the same time.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] For example: If one of the threads needs to execute an I/O request, the whole process is blocked and the threading advantage cannot be used.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] The GNU Portable Threads uses User-level threading, as does State Threads.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] SunOS 4.x implemented *light-weight processes* or LWPs.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] NetBSD 2.x+, and DragonFly BSD implement LWPs as kernel threads (1:1 model).
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] SunOS 5.2 through SunOS 5.8 as well as NetBSD 2 to NetBSD 4 implemented a two level model, multiplexing one or more user level threads on each kernel thread (M:N model).
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] SunOS 5.9 and later, as well as NetBSD 5 eliminated user threads support, returning to a 1:1 model.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] FreeBSD 6 supported both 1:1 and M:N, users could choose which one should be used with a given program using /etc/libmap.conf.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Starting with FreeBSD 7, the 1:1 became the default.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] FreeBSD 8 no longer supports the M:N model.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] In computer programming, *single-threading* is the processing of one instruction at a time.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] In the formal analysis of the variables' semantics and process state, the term *single threading* can be used differently to mean "backtracking within a single thread", which is common in the functional programming community.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Multithreading is mainly found in multitasking operating systems.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Multithreading is a widespread programming and execution model that allows multiple threads to exist within the context of one process.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] These threads share the process's resources, but are able to execute independently.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] The threaded programming model provides developers with a useful abstraction of concurrent execution.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Multithreading can also be applied to one process to enable parallel execution on a multiprocessing system.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Multithreading libraries tend to provide a function call to create a new thread, which takes a function as a parameter.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] A concurrent thread is then created which starts running the passed function and ends when the function returns.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] The thread libraries also offer data synchronization functions.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Threads in the same process share the same address space.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] This allows concurrently running code to couple tightly and conveniently exchange data without the overhead or complexity of an IPC.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] When shared between threads, however, even simple data structures become prone to race conditions if they require more than one CPU instruction to update: two threads may end up attempting to update the data structure at the same time and find it unexpectedly changing underfoot.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Bugs caused by race conditions can be very difficult to reproduce and isolate.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] To prevent this, threading application programming interfaces (APIs) offer synchronization primitives such as mutexes to lock data structures against concurrent access.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] On uniprocessor systems, a thread running into a locked mutex must sleep and hence trigger a context switch.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] On multi-processor systems, the thread may instead poll the mutex in a spinlock.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Both of these may sap performance and force processors in symmetric multiprocessing (SMP) systems to contend for the memory bus, especially if the granularity of the locking is too fine.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Other synchronization APIs include condition variables, critical sections, semaphores, and monitors.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] A popular programming pattern involving threads is that of thread pools where a set number of threads are created at startup that then wait for a task to be assigned.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] When a new task arrives, it wakes up, completes the task and goes back to waiting.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] This avoids the relatively expensive thread creation and destruction functions for every task performed and takes thread management out of the application developer's hand and leaves it to a library or the operating system that is better suited to optimize thread management.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] If all threads are busy, additional work items are placed in a queue until a thread becomes available to execute them.
[src:openmp-parallelism/thread-computing] Many programming languages support threading in some capacity.
